english:
  title: Farewell Poem for Master Huang Jin
  author: Shim Dong-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The luminous pearl from the ocean depths—
    its value beyond all reckoning.
    Not born from some aged shell,
    but spilled from the dragon's mouth.

    Among the gains and losses of this world,
    the monkeys leap in joy and rage.
    They mistake fish eyes for beauty,
    fighting to fill their treasuries with glass.

    Yet true treasure is never discarded;
    when time comes, it finds recognition.
    Once I too received advancement,
    clinging to fortune at the Golden Slope.

    But I am but a quail in my smallness—
    how could the phoenix and crane deign to turn their heads?
    So I compose this farewell verse,
    pouring out my humble heart with all sincerity.
  footnotes:
    - The 'luminous pearl' (明月珠) is a traditional symbol of hidden talent and virtue waiting to be discovered.
    - The contrast between the dragon's pearl and fish eyes represents the distinction between true worth and false value in the eyes of society.
    - The 'Golden Slope' (金坡) likely refers to the Hanlin Academy (翰林院), a prestigious institution for scholars.
    - The quail, phoenix, and crane are classical references to relative status and merit—the speaker humbly acknowledges his own limitations while expressing hope for his friend's future success.
